text:
Today is Lazy Day: Learn how to fight it. Includes Japanese Method
The alarm goes off, but he feels like staying in bed. Just five more minutes, he thinks. If this thinking is part of your routine, this article is for you and it is time for a change. The Kaisen method will help her and a bath too.

Nov 07 2019, 12:15















You're crawling around in your newly slippers after you get out of bed, you don't feel like doing anything and look at your still-lying pet and just wonder why no cat or dog was born to sleep? This International Laziness Day, November 7, is for you.
We all suffer a little from this illness, especially when we wake up, get off the couch, go to the gym, or do that most boring task. Kaisen is the Japanese method that promises to put laziness aside. The key is to create the routine of doing the same task every day at the same time for one minute.
Also read: Sexual laziness, your worst enemy. Know why?
This way, the most boring task will cease to be. Skipping, doing pushups, exercising, doing yoga, reading a book in another language are all easy tasks to accomplish because they will be done in just a minute. The idea is to take small steps to achieve greater results. And this is the basis for any situation in life. After one minute, do five until you reach the time you think is right for that task. Almost without realizing it, you'll be able to spend half an hour or more doing what you always wanted.
9 tricks to combat laziness
Work out simple tasks to perform;
Take a shower as soon as you wake up, preferably warm water;
Lazing is good for everything. It improves blood circulation and gives that brain click it's time to get up;
Have breakfast at home, paying more attention to healthy foods;
Avoid heavy food at dinner;
Set goals for your daily life;
Practice exercise early in the morning;
Go to bed early to sleep at the right times;
Learn to breathe deeply as it activates oxygen uptake and will get you excited.
Text: Ana Lúcia Sousa; Photos: IStock by Getty Images


